title: For Sale:  Sks bullpup paratrooper
postcontent:
Chinese sks paratrooper with the Shernic Gun Works SKS bullpup stock kit installed. Rifle was a little rough when I got it but with a little work and money I got it looking good. The previous person that had it (I got this thing about 6 years ago on a trade) tried to do his own gunsmithing. They tried to thread the end of the barrel but failed so I installed a muzzle break. The action cover has been ground down and I do know that it is not the stock action cover. This one is much thicker and looks like it had spots to mount a scope. It didn't have a factory mag when I got this thing so instead of fighting for one on ebay I just ordered a 30 round pro mag. The gun fires and ejects the shells great. The bolt sometimes gets hung up on the mag. I've only fired it just a few times maybe 20 rounds. The original stock was pretty much a rotten piece of wood. It was broken in a few places.
Basically I'm listing this thing as $214 for the stock and $135 for the gun.
The Tapco 20 rnd mags are the way to go with the bullpup stock.

Now the good stuff......
Shernic Gun Works SKS Bullpup Stock kit (which cost $214 with shipping)
Magpul MBus sights
Extended Mag Release
I also have a forward grip for it but no rail on the bottom of the stock on the front. can easily be ordered from SGworks.com for around $25.
and about 100 rounds of 7.62X39 ammo.
The gun fires great and ejects the shells just fine with the new stock. Still like I said in the above paragraph that the action gets hung on the mag. I think a little filing will take care of it. I'm just tired of messing with it and want someone else to enjoy working on it and enjoy shooting it.

title: For Sale:  Remington 700 VTR Desert Recon .308
location: King County - Seattle suburbs, Seattle, Washington
postcontent:
The Remington VTR, below, is chambered for the .308 Winchester cartridge. Its barrel is hammer forged into a one inch equilateral triangle, with its vertices truncated to form 0.410" joining radii. Measuring at the radii, and Ignoring the flats, there is the same 0.820" muzzle diameter found on other Remington models like the Sendero or VFS.

Triangular forms are great for stiffening spans and suppressing group dispersing vibration. Truncating the vertices of a triangle and joining the sides with arches further enhances stiffening compared to round, basic triangular or hexagonal forms. The unique shape of the VTR provides  16% greater surface area than a round barrel for improved cooling and the overall metal removal reduces barrel weight by roughly 8%.

"The new Model 700™ VTR™ desert RECON (in Digital Desert camo) features Remington's patent-pending triangular barrel contour that offers reduced weight over traditional heavy barrels, yet delivers optimum heat dissipation and rigidity.

Built on the famous Model 700™ cylindrical action, Remington® Varmint rifles are the most accurate factory-built models we produce. You'll be stunned by the degree of precision you get straight out of the box. The varmints won't be so lucky!"

Included is the rifle manual, case, and bipod mount.
The rifle has around 200 rounds max fired through it.
The only flaw with this rifle is a paint scratch on the magazine floor plate. Most people would probably replace this part to adapt a removable mag anyhow. It is not a major deal.

Thanks for reading.

title: For Sale:  Colt Anaconda .44 Magnum Double Action D.A. Revolver With Box  -- Stainless Steel
location: Long Island, Long Island, New York
postcontent:
Maker: Colt 

Model: Anaconda 

Serial Number: MM57301 

Date of Manufacture: 1990-1999 

Caliber: .44 Special / .44 Magnum 

Action Type: Single and Double Action Revolver With Swing Out Cylinder 

Markings: The left side of the barrel is marked “Colt Anaconda / 44 Magnum”. The right side of the barrel is marked “Double Action Revolver / Colt’s PT. F.A. Mfg. Co. / Hartford, Conn. U.S.A.”. The frame under the arbor and the arbor are marked “MM57301”. The left side of the frame is marked with a “Rampant Colt” logo. The left side of the grip frame at the top of the trigger guard is marked at the front with “V” and at the rear with “5”. 

Barrel Length: 6” 

Sights / Optics: This revolver is mounted with a rear sight adjustable for windage and elevation and a red ramped front sight. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are checkered rubber with finger grooves and Rampant Colt medallions. There are a few minor handling marks. The grips rate in about Excellent overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Stainless Steel 

Finish Originality: All Original 

Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the rifling is sharp. There is no erosion. 

Overall Condition: This revolver retains about 95% of its finish. There are light wear marks on the top of the barrel and receiver. There is thinning at the muzzle. The cylinder has a definite drag line and light handling marks. There are also light handling marks on the frame and barrel. The knurling on the ejector rod and serrations on the hammer are very sharp. The Screw heads on the right side of the frame shows slight disfigurement while the screw on the left side is undamaged. The markings are clear and deep. Overall, this revolver rates in about Fine condition. 

Mechanics: The lock-up on this revolver is Extremely tight. The trigger is smooth in double action, and crisp and light in single action. The action functions correctly. We did not fire this revolver. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: This revolver comes in a blue plastic case and includes an Owner’s Manual. The lid of the case is marked “Colt”. The case shows moderate wear on the bottom and light handling marks on the top. The inside of the case is fitted for the pistol and Owner’s Manual, and is in Excellent condition, as is the Owner’s Manual. 

Our Assessment: Colt introduced the Anaconda built on a new, heavy “AA” frame to compete with the Ruger Redhawk and S&W Model 29 revolvers. Our impression is that this revolver probably offers a smoother double action pull than the Ruger and is more rugged than the S&W. This revolver is great for hunting, and for those fishermen who sometimes run across unfriendly brown bears. If you download to .44 Special, it will make plinking enjoyable, and with lead bullets, won’t ruin all the meat on small game.
